        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected linewidth is around 50% of the velocity coverage of one spectral band. Two overlaping bands are required to have a good velocity coverage of the 325.15 GHz line of water vapor (redshifted to 319.3 GHz). We have selected 325.152+500 MHz and 325.152-500 MHz as frequency center for the two 1.875 GHz bands.

Although the extent of the water emission (or absorption in the case of the thermal lines of H2O observed with Herschel) is unknown, we could expect an upper size of 2" corresponding to the observed size of the molecular emission in HCN, HCO+, and CO. The size of the individual clouds contributing to the 183.3 and 325.15 GHz emission is probably much smaller, of the order of 0.3'' from Herschel modeling of the water lines. Therefore, we will need an angular resolution of 0.13'', which is provided by the most extended configuration of ALMA in Cycle2, in order to resolve the water emission at 325.15 GHz in Arp220. 

We propose to use channels 5 km/s wide to reach a S/N ratio &gt;15 in the line wings. The observed emission with the 30m IRAM radio telescope is 100 mJy at the line center and decreases to 20 mJy at velocities of 250 km/s from the line center. We request for a sensitivity over 5 km/s channels of 1.4 mJy corresponding to 1 K over a beam of 0.13". The line is 600 km/s wide, hence, some additional spectral smoothing could be done to improve the S/N in the line wings if needed. 

The total observing time is 1.74 h corresponding to on-source time of 45 min.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
